[[File:Macrochelys temminckii baiting.webm|thumb|''[[Macrochelys temminckii]]'' luring]]
'''Lingual luring''' is a form of [[aggressive mimicry]] in which a predator (typically a snake or turtle) uses its tongue to fool potential prey into approaching close to what appears to be a small wriggling worm.

Lingual lures are very well developed in young [[alligator snapping turtle]]s which wait underwater with their mouths open. The tongue is wriggled like a worm and fishes attracted to it are captured by a rapid snapping of the mouth.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Feeding Behavior of Captive-Reared Juvenile Alligator Snapping Turtles (''Macrochelys temminckii'')|first1=Mitchell B.|last1=East| first2=Brian M. |last2=Fillmore| first3=Day B. |last3=Ligon| journal=Southeastern naturalist| year=2013| volume=12| issue=4| pages=692–702}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.1979.tb01022.x|title=Luring in the Neonate Alligator Snapping Turtle (Macroclemys temminckii): Description and Experimental Analysis|journal=Zeitschrift für Tierpsychologie|volume=50|issue=2|pages=136|year=2010|last1=Drummond|first1=Hugh|last2=Gordon|first2=Elizabeth R.}}</ref>

Lingual luring has also been noted in some species of snakes including the garter snake ''[[Thamnophis atratus]]''<ref>{{cite journal|title= Evidence of Lingual-Luring by an Aquatic Snake| first1=Hartwell H. |last1=Welsh, Jr. |first2= Amy J. |last2=Lind|jstor=565240| journal=Journal of Herpetology| volume=34| issue=1| year=2000| pages=67–74|doi=10.2307/1565240 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1643/CE-08-106|title=Spatial Ecology of the Oregon Gartersnake, Thamnophis atratus hydrophilus, in a Free-Flowing Stream Environment|journal=Copeia|volume=2010|pages=75|year=2010|last1=Welsh|first1=Hartwell H.|last2=Wheeler|first2=Clara A.|last3=Lind|first3=Amy J.|url=https://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/welsh/psw_2010_welsh003.pdf}}</ref> and species of ''[[Nerodia]]'' (including ''N. sipedon'', ''N. clarkii'' and ''N. rhombifer'') - here the luring is initiated by flicking the surface of water with their tongue to attract fish.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Lingual luring by mangrove saltmarsh snakes (''Nerodia clarkii compressicauda'')| journal=Journal of Herpetology| volume=42| issue=1| pages=9–15| year=2008| author=Hansknecht, Kerry A.}}</ref> Similar behaviour has been reported in the [[snowy egret]] (''Egretta thula'') which uses tongue flicking when foraging.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Use of tongue-flicking behaviour by the snowy egret| author=Master, Terry L. | journal=Journal of Field Ornithology| volume=62| issue=3| pages=399–402|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/jfo/v062n03/p0399-p0402.pdf|year=1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Buckley|first1=P.A.| last2=Buckley| first2=F.G.| year=1968| title=Tongue-flicking by a feeding snowy-egret| journal=Auk| volume=85| page=678|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v085n04/p0678-p0678.pdf}}</ref> The puff adder ''[[Bitis arietans]]'' uses its tongue which is loosely wriggled like a worm to attract amphibian prey. The puff adder also uses its tail as a lure ([[caudal luring]]).<ref>{{cite journal|title=A lure at both ends: aggressive visual mimicry signals and prey-specific luring behaviour in an ambush-foraging snake|last1=Glaudas|first1= X. |last2= Alexander |first2=G. J.| journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |year=2017|volume=71|issue=1|pages= 1–7}}</ref>

